{"title_page": "Poet in New York", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{For|the television film|A Poet in New York}}\n{{Expand Spanish|Poeta en Nueva York|date=February 2015}}\n[[File:Autorretrato Poeta NY.jpg|thumb|right|Lorca's self-portrait for ''Poet in New York''.]]\n'''''Poet in New York''''' (in Spanish, ''Poeta en Nueva York'') is one of the most important works of Spanish author [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]. It is a body of poems composed during the visit of the poet to [[Columbia University]] in New York in the years 1929/1930. During his stay, the stock market [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|crashed]] in October 1929, an event which profoundly affected his poetic vision.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Craige |first1=Betty Jean |title=Lorca's Poet in New York: The Fall into Consciousness |date=1977 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=9780813151830 |jstor=j.ctt130jf3d |chapter=Lorca's Poet in New York }}</ref>\n\nAfter his stay in New York, Lorca traveled to Cuba, where he wrote one of the poems included in the book, \"Son de negros en Cuba\", before returning to Spain. The book was not published until 1940, after Lorca's death. Due to Franco's dictatorship, it was originally released in Mexico and the United States (translated by Rolfe Humphries).\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Public (play)|''The Public'' (play)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Poetry by Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]\n[[Category:1940 poetry books]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{For|the television film|A Poet in New York}}\n{{Expand Spanish|Poeta en Nueva York|date=February 2015}}\n[[File:Autorretrato Poeta NY.jpg|thumb|right|Lorca's self-portrait for ''Poet in New York''.]]\n'''''Poet in New York''''' (in Spanish, ''Poeta en Nueva York'') is one of the most important works of Spanish author [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]. It is a body of poems composed during the visit of the poet to [[Columbia University]] in New York in the years 1929/1930. During his stay, the stock market [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|crashed]] in October 1929, an event which profoundly affected his poetic vision.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Craige |first1=Betty Jean |title=Lorca's Poet in New York: The Fall into Consciousness |date=1977 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=9780813151830 |jstor=j.ctt130jf3d |chapter=Lorca's Poet in New York }}</ref>\n\nAfter his stay in New York, Lorca traveled to Cuba, where he wrote one of the poems included in the book, \"Son de negros en Cuba\", before returning to Spain. The book was not published until 1940, after Lorca's death. Due to Franco's dictatorship, it was originally released in Mexico and the United States (translated by Rolfe Humphries).\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Public (play)|''The Public'' (play)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Poetry by Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]\n[[Category:1940 books]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1940 bookstoCategory:1940 poetry booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poet_in_New_York"}
{"title_page": "Padatik (poetry collection)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Padatik (disambiguation){{!}}Padatik}}\n{{Infobox book\n<!-- |italic title = (see above) -->\n| name             = Padatik\n| image            = Padatik 1940.png\n| alt              = Padatik book front cover\n| caption          = Padatik book front cover\n| author           = [[Subhash Mukhopadhyay (poet)|Subhash Mukhopadhyay]]\n| title_orig       = \n| translator       = \n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     = \n| country          = India\n| language         = Bengali\n| series           = \n| subject          = \n| genre            = Poetry\n| publisher        = \n| pub_date         = 1940\n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type       = \n| pages            = \n| isbn             = \n| oclc             = \n| dewey            = \n| congress         = \n| preceded_by      = \n| followed_by      = \n}}\n'''''Padatik''''' ('''''The Foot Soldier''''') first published in 1940<ref name=\"Das1995\">{{cite book|author=Sisir Kumar Das|title=History of Indian Literature: 1911-1956, struggle for freedom : triumph and tragedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&pg=PA538|accessdate=24 June 2012|date=1 January 1995|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-7201-798-9|pages=538\u2013}}</ref> is a [[Bengali language|Bengali]] book of poems written by [[Subhash Mukhopadhyay (poet)|Subhash Mukhopadhyay]]. This was Mukhopadhyay's first published book.<ref name=\"MukherjeeBandyop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa1996\">{{cite book|author1=Subhash Mukherjee|author2=Surabhi Bandyop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa|title=The Cape|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpuHT_aV1wMC&pg=PP3|accessdate=24 June 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-0936-8|pages=3\u2013}}</ref> This book created a storm in Bengali literature. Mukhopadhyay wrote this book as a representative of a political party.<ref name=\"A Poet who celebrates life\">{{cite web|title=A Poet who celebrates life|url=http://newstoday.com.bd/index.php?option=details&news_id=29871&date=2011-06-10|publisher=News Today|accessdate=24 June 2012}}</ref> Mukhopadhyay in his personal life was a consistent [[Marxism|Marxist]].<ref name=\"Zbavitel1976\">{{cite book|author=[[Du\u0161an Zbavitel]]|title=A History of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNHqRVM7kIcC&pg=PA291|accessdate=24 June 2012|year=1976|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-01673-5|pages=291\u2013}}</ref> In this book, poet showed his zeal to redeem the poor and suffering masses from exploitation.<ref name=\"A Poet who celebrates life\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n*For the popularity of the book Subhash Mukhopadhyay is often called \"''Padatik'' Subhash Mukhopadhyay\" or \"''Padatik'' poet Subhash Mukhopadhyay\",\n*In 2009 Sealdah-NJP Express was named \"Padatik Express\" after this book in memory of the poet.<ref name=\"Tracks & trains for \u2018backward\u2019 region\">{{cite news|title=Tracks & trains for \u2018backward\u2019 region|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1091005/jsp/siliguri/story_11575208.jsp|accessdate=24 June 2012|newspaper=Telegraph Calcutta|date=5 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:1940 poetry books]]\n[[Category:Bengali poetry]]\n[[Category:Indian poetry collections]]\n\n\n{{poetry-collection-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Padatik (disambiguation){{!}}Padatik}}\n{{Infobox book\n<!-- |italic title = (see above) -->\n| name             = Padatik\n| image            = Padatik 1940.png\n| alt              = Padatik book front cover\n| caption          = Padatik book front cover\n| author           = [[Subhash Mukhopadhyay (poet)|Subhash Mukhopadhyay]]\n| title_orig       = \n| translator       = \n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     = \n| country          = India\n| language         = Bengali\n| series           = \n| subject          = \n| genre            = Poetry\n| publisher        = \n| pub_date         = 1940\n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type       = \n| pages            = \n| isbn             = \n| oclc             = \n| dewey            = \n| congress         = \n| preceded_by      = \n| followed_by      = \n}}\n'''''Padatik''''' ('''''The Foot Soldier''''') first published in 1940<ref name=\"Das1995\">{{cite book|author=Sisir Kumar Das|title=History of Indian Literature: 1911-1956, struggle for freedom : triumph and tragedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&pg=PA538|accessdate=24 June 2012|date=1 January 1995|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-7201-798-9|pages=538\u2013}}</ref> is a [[Bengali language|Bengali]] book of poems written by [[Subhash Mukhopadhyay (poet)|Subhash Mukhopadhyay]]. This was Mukhopadhyay's first published book.<ref name=\"MukherjeeBandyop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa1996\">{{cite book|author1=Subhash Mukherjee|author2=Surabhi Bandyop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa|title=The Cape|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpuHT_aV1wMC&pg=PP3|accessdate=24 June 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-0936-8|pages=3\u2013}}</ref> This book created a storm in Bengali literature. Mukhopadhyay wrote this book as a representative of a political party.<ref name=\"A Poet who celebrates life\">{{cite web|title=A Poet who celebrates life|url=http://newstoday.com.bd/index.php?option=details&news_id=29871&date=2011-06-10|publisher=News Today|accessdate=24 June 2012}}</ref> Mukhopadhyay in his personal life was a consistent [[Marxism|Marxist]].<ref name=\"Zbavitel1976\">{{cite book|author=[[Du\u0161an Zbavitel]]|title=A History of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNHqRVM7kIcC&pg=PA291|accessdate=24 June 2012|year=1976|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-01673-5|pages=291\u2013}}</ref> In this book, poet showed his zeal to redeem the poor and suffering masses from exploitation.<ref name=\"A Poet who celebrates life\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n*For the popularity of the book Subhash Mukhopadhyay is often called \"''Padatik'' Subhash Mukhopadhyay\" or \"''Padatik'' poet Subhash Mukhopadhyay\",\n*In 2009 Sealdah-NJP Express was named \"Padatik Express\" after this book in memory of the poet.<ref name=\"Tracks & trains for \u2018backward\u2019 region\">{{cite news|title=Tracks & trains for \u2018backward\u2019 region|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1091005/jsp/siliguri/story_11575208.jsp|accessdate=24 June 2012|newspaper=Telegraph Calcutta|date=5 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:1940 books]]\n[[Category:Bengali poetry]]\n[[Category:Indian poetry collections]]\n\n\n{{poetry-collection-stub}}\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1940 bookstoCategory:1940 poetry booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padatik_(poetry_collection)"}
{"title_page": "Carlos Sanz (historian of cartography)", "text_new": "'''Carlos Sanz''' (1903-1981) was a Spanish publisher and historian of [[cartography]] based in [[Madrid]]. He died at the end of 1981.<ref>Tony Campbell, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1150749?seq=1 Chronicle for 1981\u2013], ''[[Imago Mundi]], Vol. 34 (1982), pp.90-98.</ref> He donated books and maps to the [[University of Miami]].<ref>[http://scholar.library.miami.edu/maps/sanz.html The Carlos Sanz Collection], [[University of Miami]].</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* (ed.) ''La Carta de Col\u00f3n anunciando el descubrimiento del Nuevo Mundo, 15 febrero-14 marzo, 1493'' by [[Christopher Columbus]], 1956\n* ''Primitivas relaciones de Espa\u00f1a con Asia y Ocean\u00eda: los dos primeros libros impresos en Filipinas, mas un tercero en discordia'', 1957\n* (ed.) ''Primera historia de China, Sevilla, 1577'' by [[Bernardino de Escalente]], 1958\n* ''Bibliograf\u00eda general de la Carta de Col\u00f3n'', 1958\n* (ed.) ''Bibliotheca Americana vetustissima; a description of works relating to America published between the years 1492 and 1551'' by [[Henry Harrisse]]. Madrid, 1958\n* ''La Geographia de Ptolomeo, ampliada con los primeros mapas impresos de Am\u00e9rica, desde 1507; estudio bibliogr\u00e1fico y cr\u00edtico, con el cat\u00e1logo de las ediciones aparecidas desde 1475 a 1883, comentado e ilustrado'', 1959\n* ''El nombre Am\u00e9rica; libros y mapas que lo impusieron'', 1959\n* ''El gran secreto de la Carta de Col\u00f3n (cr\u00edtica hist\u00f3rica) y otras adiciones a la Bibliotheca Americana vetustissima'', 1959\n* ''Bibliotheca Americana vetustissima: comentario cr\u00edtico e \u00edndice general cronol\u00f3gico de los seis vol\u00famenes que componen la obra'', 1960\n* ''Mapas antiguos del mundo: siglos XV-XVI''. 2 vols. Madrid, 1962.\n* (ed.) ''Diario de Col\u00f3n; libro de la primera navegaci\u00f3n y descubrimiento de las Indias'' by [[Christopher Columbus]], 1962\n* ''Cartografia hist\u00f3rica de los descubrimientos australes'', 1967\n* ''Australia. Su descubrimiento y denominaci\u00f3n. Con la reproducci\u00f3n facs\u00edmil de Memorial n\u00famero 8 de Quir\u00f3s en espa\u00f1ol original, y en las diversas traducciones contempor\u00e1neas'', 1973\n* ''Hacia el descubrimiento del verdadero ser de la historia?: conferencia pronunciada en la Fundaci\u00f3n Universitaria Espa\u00f1ola el d\u00eda 21 de marzo de 1974'', 1974\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sanz, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:Historians of cartography]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish historians]]\n[[Category:Spanish publishers (people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Carlos Sanz''' (1903-1981) was a Spanish publisher and historian of [[cartography]] based in [[Madrid]]. He died at the end of 1981.<ref>Tony Campbell, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1150749?seq=1 Chronicle for 1981\u2013], ''[[Imago Mundi]], Vol. 34 (1982), pp.90-98.</ref> He donated books and maps to the [[University of Miami]].<ref>[http://scholar.library.miami.edu/maps/sanz.html The Carlos Sanz Collection], [[University of Miami]].</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* (ed.) ''La Carta de Col\u00f3n anunciando el descubrimiento del Nuevo Mundo, 15 febrero-14 marzo, 1493'' by [[Christopher Columbus]], 1956\n* ''Primitivas relaciones de Espa\u00f1a con Asia y Ocean\u00eda: los dos primeros libros impresos en Filipinas, mas un tercero en discordia'', 1957\n* (ed.) ''Primera historia de China, Sevilla, 1577'' by [[Bernardino de Escalente]], 1958\n* ''Bibliograf\u00eda general de la Carta de Col\u00f3n'', 1958\n* (ed.) ''Bibliotheca Americana vetustissima; a description of works relating to America published between the years 1492 and 1551'' by [[Henry Harrisse]]. Madrid, 1958\n* ''La Geographia de Ptolomeo, ampliada con los primeros mapas impresos de Am\u00e9rica, desde 1507; estudio bibliogr\u00e1fico y cr\u00edtico, con el cat\u00e1logo de las ediciones aparecidas d