{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Viral outbreak in the United States}}\n{{short description|none}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n<!--NOTE: Please discuss on talk page before putting a \"current event\" template here. This is intended for short-term use only per advice at Template:Current-->\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak USA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million residents by state\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = United States\n| first_case      = [[Everett, Washington]]<!--no source, not mentioned in the article-->\n| arrival_date    = January 15, 2020<ref name= NEJMFirstCase/><br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheikh |first1=Knvul |last2=Rabin |first2=Roni Caryn |title=The Coronavirus: What Scientists Have Learned So Far |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/what-is-coronavirus.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 9,441 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\">{{cite web| last = Johns Hopkins CSSE| title = Coronavirus COVID19 (2019-nCoV)| work = Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases| format = ArcGIS| accessdate = April 5, 2020| url = https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6}}</ref><br /> 7,616 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\">{{cite news |title=Cases in U.S. |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |agency=Center for Disease Control}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 337,620 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/><br /> 304,826 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 16,826 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.gov/}}\n}}\nAn ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a new infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), was first confirmed to have spread to the [[:United States of America]] in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty U.S. states, the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=samoanews.com|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|04|06|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks third in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first known case of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} in the U.S. was confirmed on January 20, 2020, in a 35-year-old returnee from [[Wuhan]], China, five days earlier.<ref name=NEJMFirstCase>{{cite journal |vauthors=Holshue ML, DeBolt C, Lindquist S, Lofy KH, et al |title=First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=382 |issue=10 |pages=929\u2013936 |date=March 2020 |pmid=32004427 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 }}</ref> The [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] was established on January 29.<ref name=\"Jan29WH\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|date=January 29, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|publisher=[[White House]]|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force}}</ref> Two days later, the [[Trump administration]] declared a [[public health emergency (United States)|public health emergency]] and announced restrictions on travelers arriving from China.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/01/31/801686524/trump-declares-coronavirus-a-public-health-emergency-and-restricts-travel-from-c |publisher= [[NPR]] |date= January 31, 2020 |accessdate= March 18, 2020 |title= Trump Declares Coronavirus A Public Health Emergency And Restricts Travel From China |author= Aubrey, Allison}}</ref> On February 26, the first case in the U.S. in a person with \"no known exposure to the virus through travel or close contact with a known infected individual\" was confirmed by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) in northern California.<ref name=HomeGrown>{{cite news |url= https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article240674471.html |work= [[The Sacramento Bee]] | title= First U.S. coronavirus case of unknown origin confirmed in Northern California, CDC says |author= Smith, Darrell and Cathie Anderson |date= February 26, 2020 |accessdate= March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe United States got off to a slow start in [[COVID-19 testing]].<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=WangMarch22/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/28/trump-coronavirus-politics-us-health-disaster|title=The missing six weeks: how Trump failed the biggest test of his life|date=March 28, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=McCarthy|first2=Tom|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Until the end of February, the [[Food and Drug Administration|Food and Drug Administration (FDA)]] procedures forbade laboratories other than the CDC from releasing test results to patients, even if they followed internationally recognized test protocols. The CDC developed and distributed test kits of its own, but many of them were found to have a manufacturing flaw in a non-essential component, which made the kit illegal to use until the protocol was changed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/cdc-coronavirus-testing-error-resolved-by-throwing-away-reagent-2020-3|title=For more than 2 weeks, state labs were told they couldn't use the CDC's coronavirus tests\u2014but the tests could have been used all along|first=Aria|last=Bendix|website=Business Insider|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=WangMarch22/> On February 29, the FDA began allowing public health agencies, hospitals, and private companies to develop tests and perform testing, and by mid-March private companies were shipping hundreds of thousands of tests.<ref name=LeeMarch21/> The FDA initially had very restrictive guidelines on who was allowed to be tested, but on March{{nbsp}}5, it said anyone with a doctor's order could be tested.<ref name=WangMarch22/> As of March 25, at least 418,000 tests had been conducted,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Subramaniam |first1=Tara |last2=Lybrand |first2=Holmes |title=Fact Check: US has done more coronavirus tests than South Korea, but not per person |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/coronavirus-testing-trump-south-korea-fact-check/index.html |publisher=CNN}}</ref> and by April{{nbsp}}2 the number had reached 1,280,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2020/coronavirus-testing-by-state-chart-of-new-cases/|title=Live tracker: How many coronavirus cases have been reported in each U.S. state?|last=Jin|first=Beatrice|date=March 30, 2020|work=Politico|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC warned that widespread transmission of the disease may force large numbers of people to seek hospitalization and other healthcare, which may overload healthcare systems.<ref name=\"CDC COVID-19 Situation Summary\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation Summary |last=CDC |publisher=CDC |accessdate=March 7, 2020|date=March 7, 2020 }}</ref> Since March 19, 2020, the U.S. [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] has advised U.S. citizens to avoid all international travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory\u2014Do Not Travel|website=travel.state.gov}}</ref> On March 16, the White House advised against any gatherings of more than 10 people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liptak |first1=Kevin |title=White House advises public to avoid groups of more than 10, asks people to stay away from bars and restaurants |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/politics/white-house-guidelines-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In mid-March 2020, the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA) told the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (USACE) to plan to construct new facilities, including leased hotels and other buildings, and to convert them for use as [[hospitals]] and [[intensive care unit]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48927-rep-defazio-fema-asks-army-corps-to-help-build-emergency-health-facilities|title=Rep. DeFazio: FEMA Asks Army Corps to Help Build Emergency Health Facilities|last1=Ichniowski|first1=Tom|last2=Rubin|first2=Debra K.|date=March 18, 2020|work=Engineering News-Record|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/balajis/status/1242029099310133248|title=Ok. It's just one clip. But it's by far the most intelligent thing I've heard any government official say in the last few months. Further increases likelihood the military will take over COVID19 response in the near future. |website=twitter.com/usarmy|first=Balaji S.|last=Srinivasan|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref> [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|State and local responses]] to the outbreak have included prohibitions and cancellation of large-scale gatherings, the closure of schools and other educational institutions, the cancellation of [[trade fair|trade shows]], [[Convention (meeting)|conventions]], and music festivals, and the cancellation and suspension of sporting events and leagues.<ref name=\"nyt sports\">{{Cite news|last=Deb|first=Sopan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/sports/basketball/warriors-coronavirus-fans.html|title=Sports Leagues Bar Fans and Cancel Games Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 11, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020|last2=Cacciola|first2=Scott|issn=0362-4331|last3=Stein|first3=Marc}}</ref>\n\n==Current number of non-repatriated cases by states and territories==\n\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\"><!--serious rendering issues in current article with it floated to the right-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States cases by state}}</div>\n\nThe CDC publishes official numbers every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, reporting several categories of cases: individual travelers, people who contracted the disease from other people within the U.S., and repatriated citizens who returned to the U.S. from crisis locations, such as [[Wuhan]], where the disease originated, and the cruise ship ''Diamond Princess''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|title=International Locations with Confirmed COVID-19 Cases|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222072600/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|archive-date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n{{gallery\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed cases ({{As of|2020|04|04|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|None confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|<1,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|1,000\u20134,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|5,000\u20139,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|10,000\u201319,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|20,000\u2013120,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>120,000 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Pandemic Deaths in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed deaths ({{As of|2020|04|04|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|None confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|<50 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|50\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|100\u2013199 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|200\u2013399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|400\u20134,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>4,000 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States by counties (Confirmed).svg|Confirmed COVID-19 cases by county ({{As of|2020|04|01|lc=y|df=US}})\n| File:Lab-specimens-tested.jpg|Number of tests done per day in the United States by the CDC and public health labs (private labs are not included)<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing-in-us.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>{{br}}\u00a7 Data during this period are pending.\n| File:CoViD-19 US.svg|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]]\n|title=}}\n\nThe following numbers are based on CDC data. However, CDC data is incomplete. In most U.S. locations, testing for some time was performed only on symptomatic people with a history of travel to Wuhan or with close contact to such people.<ref name=\"Madrigal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/925233|title=Persons Evaluated for 2019 Novel Coronavirus\u2014US, Jan 2020|website=Medscape|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/new-york-man-denied-coronavirus-test-japan-trip-fever-cough-2020-3|title=A New York City man wasn't tested for the coronavirus even though he had symptoms and had gone to Japan. It highlights the troublingly limited scope of US testing.|first=Morgan|last=McFall-Johnsen|website=Business Insider|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> A quarantined nurse in California, showing symptoms of COVID-19 but without a travel history, said she was denied testing by the CDC in early March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/08/u-s-response-to-the-covid-19-coronavirus-moves-from-containment-to-mitigation|title=US response to the COVID-19 coronavirus moves from 'containment' to 'mitigation'|date=March 8, 2020|first=Jonathan|last=Shieber|work=TechCrunch}}</ref> CDC testing protocols did not include non-travelling patients with no known contact with China until February 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/27/health/us-cases-coronavirus-community-transmission/index.html|title=The CDC has changed its criteria for testing patients for coronavirus after the first case of unknown origin was confirmed|first1=Sarah |last1=Moon |first2=Holly |last2=Yan |first3=Jen |last3=Christensen |first4=Christina|last4=Maxouris|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original CDC-developed tests sent out on February{{nbsp}}5 turned out to be faulty.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/trumps-misplaced-blame-on-obama-for-coronavirus-tests/|title=Trump's Misplaced Blame on Obama for Coronavirus Tests|first=Jessica|last=McDonald|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On February 29, the FDA announced that labs would be allowed to do their own in-house testing immediately, independently of CDC testing, as long as they complete an emergency use authorization (EUA) within 15 days.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\"/> In Washington, state regulators at one point told health care workers to stop testing previously collected samples from an existing non-COVID19 flu study.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/world/coronavirus-news.html|title=U.S. Cases of Coronavirus Surpass 1,000; British Health Minister Is Infected|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the CDC reported that 37,824 specimens had been tested for COVID-19, 4,484 of which were tested by CDC labs, and 33,340 tested by U.S. public health labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|title=Testing in the U.S.|date=March 16, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316204847/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The number of deaths is also probably an undercount, as it leaves out some Americans who tested positive but did not have the virus listed on their death certificates, and others who died without being tested. The CDC says that it will issue an official estimate of coronavirus deaths in 2021, but that current estimates may not be reliable.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kliff |first1=Sarah |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |title=Official Counts Understate the U.S. Coronavirus Death Toll |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/us/coronavirus-deaths-undercount.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimates a peak in deaths per day by April 15, with a total of about 80,000 deaths in the United States due to coronavirus by August. If a low [[case fatality rate]] of 2% is assumed, then the 80,000 deaths implies 4,000,000 positive cases by August.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME)|url=https://covid19.healthdata.org/projections|title=COVID-19 Projections|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===CDC reported U.S. totals===\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases chart}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===State number of non-repatriated cases by date {{anchor|State number of reported cases by date}}===\n\n{{main|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases}}\n<!--Template for Graph:Chart is at [[Template:Graph:Chart]]-->\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=400\n|colors=#FF4343\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n<!--PLease clipboard copy the \"}x=...\" and \"y1=...\" lines from the log plot of total cases when you update these charts-->\n\n<!--Search string CASES_X-->\n|x= Feb 26, Feb 27, Feb 28, Feb 29, Mar 1, Mar 2, Mar 3, Mar 4, Mar 5, Mar 6, Mar 7, Mar 8, Mar 9, Mar 10, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 15, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 18, Mar 19, Mar 20, Mar 21, Mar 22, Mar 23, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 31, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4, Apr 5\n\n<!--Search string CASES_Y-->\n|y1=15, 15, 19, 24, 42, 57, 85, 111, 175, 252, 353, 497, 645, 936, 1205, 1598, 2163, 2825, 3501, 4373, 5662, 8074, 12018, 17439, 23710, 32341, 42749, 52685, 64916, 81966, 101022, 121105, 140223, 160686, 186082, 212814, 241626, 273808, 307876, 333593\n\n|yScaleType=<!--log This is the line that makes this plot have a log axis, so le